            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">Shlihat is a rural place 15 km to the southwest of the governorate’s capital El Kef. According to the Tunisian historian Mohamed Tlili, the toponym harks back to a Berber tribal group, which allied with the great Houwara tribe Sharen (Šārin). Coming from the Kefian Mellegue hills, the Šlīḥ tribe settled the place from the 1970s on. A local calls himself a Shlihi (<hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">šlī</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">ḥi</hi>) or herself a Shlihiya (<hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">šlī</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">ḥ</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">īya</hi>). In this area of low population density, most residents run their own farms. Traditionally, olive trees were planted under the advantageous climatic conditions the place offers. Provided that there is an access to water sources, people nowadays cultivate a wealth of further vegetables and fruits.</p>
            </div>
